		<content:encoded><![CDATA[This weekend, I attended my first game jam with the <a href="http://www.codeliberation.org/">Code Liberation Foundation</a>. I heard about the event two days prior, and decided to attend their OpenFrameworks workshop on Thursday as preparation for the game jam. Despite limited documentation, <a href="http://www.openframeworks.cc">OpenFrameworks</a> is fairly easy to get into, especially with a teacher like Nina Freeman showing you the ropes.

Nina taught us the basics in a fun and engaging manner that was a far cry from my often painfully sluggish and somewhat robotic college classes. Slowly, some of the programming and data structures I learned in college started to come back to me. It was a candid reminder that, more often than not, learning by doing is far more effective than a lecture or rote memorization.

Yet, would that be enough to prepare me for two full days of designing and programming my very own video game? I can say with great satisfaction that, yes, it can! Here is a brief video of our game, I.T.: IntraTerrestrial.


[vimeo 75723630 w=550]
<br />

We kicked off the event on Friday with the theme "angles." In a room full of women, we seemed to form into groups organically as we reeled off ideas to one another. Right from the start, it was like working with good friends, though I didn't know a soul in the room. After developing the basic idea of a floating balloon avoiding being popped by sharp angles, and organizing ourselves into roles under the group name, SHELIUM, we said our goodbyes until the next day.

Saturday, Lauren Gardner of Babycastles came to speak and encourage us with words of wisdom. Later, we struggled for hours with attempting to get Github and XCode to play nicely with each other, to no avail. We decided to set it aside and focus on the code, not the tools.

I turned my attention to the unique challenge of a vertically scrolling background. I already knew how to make objects move in OpenFrameworks, but how could I accomplish this with an object that spanned the width and height of the screen? After some experimentation, I prototyped some working code that would allow the background to scroll ever faster to the bottom of the screen, rather than sideways as was typical of a side-scrolling video game. I left that day feeling accomplished.

Sunday, I worked to replace the rectangular shapes I had drawn the previous day with multiple images. With so little time left and representatives from the press interrupting with photos and interviews in the background, I struggled to stay focused and remain calm. I asked our lovely teachers and my teammates for assistance, but I was certain that there must be a simpler solution. Then suddenly, on a casual walk to the bathroom to get away from my computer screen for a bit, the solution came to me. Because the code followed a distinct pattern, I could rely on a for loop and a series of conditional statements to stack and repeat a series of images as they scrolled to the bottom. It was so simple it seemed stupid, but sure enough, it worked!

With no time to spare, we finished our game with basic functionality and shared it with NYU Poly students. While it was not as functional as the games by the Computer Science majors, it gave me a great deal of confidence about expanding my knowledge of programming, and participating in more game jams!

With all the controversy surrounding women and the depiction of women in video games, I am certain that if we ever hope to change the tech and game industry, we have to put in the hard work it will take to change the ratio and support the female computer scientists and game designers of today and tomorrow.

Check out <a href="http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/women-create-video-games-at-nyu-polytechnic-institute-1.6170525">this coverage of the event on the local news</a>! I make an appearance at the end of the video.]]></content:encoded>
